"We consider the following problem. A signature authority issues RSA-signatures of certain types to an individual, and the individual tries, by using the signatures he received, to compute an RSA-signature of a type not issued by the authority. Is the individual able to do this? The RSA-signatures are products of rational powers of residue classes modulo the composite number N of the underlying RSA-system, and the residue classes are chosen at random by the signature authority. The rational exponents in the product determine the type of the signature."
